As an example, the Norwegian character ø is encoded as %c3%b8.  A URL with this is not considered valid in the application navigator in Confluence.

It's impossible add links with Google Chrome when you edit an article.

Steps to reproduce.

1. Edit or create an article.
2. Create a link
3. Search previous article.
4. Click on save

After this action nothing seems happens. If you open the Chrome Dev Tools, this error appears.

Property 'scrollTo' of object [object global] is not a function 

The code break in this point, "scrollTop" function.

{code}
  if (AJS.$.browser.safari) {
     var G = AJS.$(window).scrollTop();
     AJS.$(window).scrollTop(10 + 5 * (G == 10)).scrollTop(G)
  }
{code}

I notice this function works fine on Firefox and Sarafi, but doesn't on Chrome.

If you use a different selector instead "window", get the same effect and works on Safari as well.

My solution.

{code}
  if (AJS.$.browser.safari) {
     var G = AJS.$(window).scrollTop();
     AJS.$('html body').scrollTop(10 + 5 * (G == 10)).scrollTop(G)
  }
{code}

I notice this issue in last versions of Confluence, I migrated with the last versions but the error persists only with Google Chrome.

